07095nam a22009135i 9780271078120DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710781207 a10.1515/97802710781202doi  a(DE-B1597)583799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aP301b.T44 2016eb 7aLAN0040002bisacsh04a80822300aText + Field :bInnovations in Rhetorical Method /ced. by Sara L. McKinnon, Robert Glenn Howard, Karma R. Chávez, Robert Asen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Articulating Text and Field in the Nodes of Rhetorical Scholarship -- t1 Interrogating the “Field” -- t2 Rhetorical Field Methods in the Tradition of Imitatio -- t3 From Guåhan and Back: Navigating a “Both/Neither” Analytic for Rhetorical Field Methods -- t4 Feeling Rhetorical Critics: Another Affective- Emotional Field Method for Rhetorical Studies -- t5 Embodied Judgment: A Call for a Phronetic Orientation in Rhetorical Ethnography -- t6 “Pa’ que tú lo sepas”: Experiences with Co- presence in Puerto Rico -- t7 It’s Like a Prairie Fire! Rhetorics of Trust and Reciprocity in the Texas Coal Plant Opposition Movement -- t8 Being, Evoking, and Reflecting from the Field: A Case for Critical Ethnography in Audience- Centered Rhetorical Criticism -- t9 Holographic Rhetoric: De/Colonizing Public Memory at Pueblo Grande -- t10 Context Drives Method: Studying Social Media Use in a War Zone -- tAfterword: Decentralizing and Regenerating the Field -- tList of Contributors -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRhetorical critics have long had a troubled relationship with method, viewing it as at times opening up provocative avenues of inquiry, and at other times as closing off paths toward meaningful engagement with texts. Text + Field shifts scholarly attention from this conflicted history, looking instead to the growing number of scholars who are supplementing text-based scholarship by venturing out into the field, where rhetoric is produced, enacted, and consumed. These field-based practices involve observation, ethnographic interviews, and performance. They are not intended to displace text-based approaches; rather, they expand the idea of method by helping rhetorical scholars arrive at new and complementary answers to long-standing disciplinary questions about text, context, audience, judgment, and ethics. The first volume in rhetoric and communication to directly address the relevance, processes, and implications of using field methods to augment traditional scholarship, Text + Field provides a framework for adapting these new tools to traditional rhetorical inquiry.Aside from the editors, the contributors are Roberta Chevrette, Kathleen M. de Onís, Danielle Endres, Joshua P. Ewalt, Alina Haliliuc, Aaron Hess, Jamie Landau, Michael Middleton, Tiara R. Na’puti, Jessy J. Ohl, Phaedra C. Pezzullo, Damien Smith Pfister, Samantha Senda-Cook, Lisa Silvestri, and Valerie Thatcher.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aRhetoricxFieldwork. 0aRhetoricxMethodology. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aAsen, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsen, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChevrette, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChávez, Karma R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChávez, Karma R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEndres, Daniell